            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-02-02T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-02-02T08:00:00-05:00" n="1240" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1240">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/2–249: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-02-02T21:00:00+08:00">February 2, 1949—9 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 3—1:59 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>300. Re Shanghai’s 279, January 28, repeated Nanking. As comment on reftel,
                    Embassy states that in performance protective function in Nanking district it
                    expects to continue issue posters identifying and protecting American property
                    this city. However, American property here insignificant compared to Shanghai
                    and Embassy believes problem arising widespread use of posters should be decided
                    by Consulates for localities their districts, subject Departmental approval.</p>
                <p>Sent Department, repeated Shanghai 133.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
